Adjust rack to middle position and preheat #oven{} to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; cut crosswise into ½-inch-thick half-moons. Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{6%ounce} on a diagonal into ½-inch-thick pieces.

Halve @mandarin orange{1}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens.

In a #small pot{}, combine @jasmine rice{1/2%cup}, ¾ cup water (1½ cups for 4 servings), and a pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook, covered, until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, toss zucchini and carrots on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @cooking oil{4%teaspoon}, @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on middle rack until browned and tender, ~{18-20%minutes}.

While veggies roast, in a #medium bowl{}, whisk together juice from whole mandarin (both for 4 servings), @chicken stock concentrate{1}, @sweet thai chili sauce{2%ounce}, @soy sauce{2%tablespoon}, half the @cornstarch{1%tablespoon} (all for 4), ½ cup water (1 cup for 4), and @sugar{1%teaspoon} (2 tsp for 4).

> Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.

Pat @pork chops{10%ounce} dry with paper towels and season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add pork and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per side.

Turn off heat; transfer pork to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for pork over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites and cook, stirring occasionally, until fragrant and soft, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Add mandarin chili sauce. Reduce heat to medium; cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce begins to thicken, ~{2-4%minutes}. Turn off heat. Stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4 servings) until melted.

Add pork to sauce and turn to coat.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Divide rice and veggies between #plates{}. Top rice with pork and drizzle with any remaining sauce. Garnish with scallion greens and serve.